    <text>
        <body>
            <div style="handwritten" type="letter" xml:id="d.1">
                <head type="title">Camillo Ghilino to Miklós Oláh (Milan, 27 August 1534)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p xml:id="reg.p.1">Candiano is moving to Belgium with his wife. Ghilino
                            wishes the Queen’s health would improve! The Turkish fleet keeps
                            alternating between destroying the Adriatic cities and the kingdom of
                            Naples, and it is unclear where and when they will continue; the
                            Emperor’s troops will be able to attack them with success if they head
                            towards Africa. Ghilino is travelling to King Ferdinand I now; the
                            bearer of the letter has told him that he can deliver the reply between
                            them within 15 days, Oláh should also make sure that his happens. If
                            Oláh’s letter arrives in Ghilino’s absence, his lord, Francesco II
                            Sforza will open it.</p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb/>
                <p xml:id="p.1">Idem Nicolao Olao salutem. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.2"><persName>Candianus</persName><note type="critic" xml:id="note.1"
                        >Ambrogio Candiano.</note> noster tandem in
                        <persName>principis</persName><note type="critic" xml:id="note.2">Francesco
                        II Sforza.</note> nostri sententiam uxorem traxit, quam secum propediem ad
                    vos in Belgas ducet.<note type="critic" xml:id="note.3">On the antecedents and
                        this plan, see Ep. 490. Cap. 1.<ref>olahus.tei.15340531_1</ref></note>
                    Utinam reginae nostrae valetudo indies firmior fiat, ne medicorum ope amplius
                    indigeat. Classis Turcica spelunca fundos et pleraque alia oppidula in litore
                    maris Adriatici, tum regni Neapolitani depopulata est, nunc, quo cursum
                    direxerit, ignoratur. Classis caesaris paratur, opportuneque eam invadet, si in
                    Aphricam traiciet, superiorque omnino erit. Ego ad <persName>regem</persName>
                    nostrum Romanum<note type="critic" xml:id="note.4">I.e. Romanorum.</note>
                    quatriduo post proficiscar, cum illic ero, dabo operam, ut a me multa
                    intelligas. Tabellarius, qui has tibi deferet, pollicetur se ex novo quodam
                    collegio istic facto litteras vestras nostrasque ultro in quindecim diebus
                        <milestone unit="pb"/>delaturum, te obtestor, ut me quamprimum moneas,
                    quantum fidei isti praestare possimus. Ego si in tuarum litterarum adventu
                    absens fuero, constitui, ut <persName>princeps</persName> ipse tuas aperiat, qui
                    et te diligit et amat. <persName>Reginam</persName> nostram di ad vota
                    felicitent, cui <del corresp="Olahus">ex te</del> commodari valde cupio, et
                    pedes deosculor. Virginem clarissimam <persName>Lucretiam</persName><note
                        type="critic" xml:id="note.5">Lucretia Caballis (vom Ross).</note> meo
                    nomine salvere iubebis. <persName>Bannisium</persName><note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.6">Jakob Radich de Bannisis the Younger.</note> meum item tuum
                    salutabis meis verbis, simulque dabitis operam, ut globus meus conficiatur.
                    Vale, Amicorum Optime, et me, ut facis, ama. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.3"><placeName>Mediolano</placeName> VI. Kalendas Septembris 1534.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
